<div id="review_42729080" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/42729080" />
    <a title="Kathleen Hagen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1291703-kathleen-hagen"><img alt="Kathleen Hagen" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/42729080?book_show_action=true">Jan 11, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kathleen Hagen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kathleen Hagen" href="/user/show/1291703-kathleen-hagen">Kathleen Hagen</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291703-kathleen-hagen?shelf=2007-audio-books">2007-audio-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291703-kathleen-hagen?shelf=2007-general-fiction">2007-general-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer42729080" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16531473278767410773">The Day of the Scorpion, by Paul Scott. Book 2 of the Raj Quartet. B-plus. Cassette book borrowed from the Library for the Blind.<br/>In my opinion not as good as The Jewel in the Crown. This book is dated immediately after the first one. At the beginning of the book, Harry is still imprisoned allegedly for the rape and assault of Daphne Manners. The best section of this book was the interview he had with a policeman about what happened, why he was arrested, and Merrick’s part in the whole affair and</span>
  <span id="freeText16531473278767410773" style="display:none">The Day of the Scorpion, by Paul Scott. Book 2 of the Raj Quartet. B-plus. Cassette book borrowed from the Library for the Blind.<br />In my opinion not as good as The Jewel in the Crown. This book is dated immediately after the first one. At the beginning of the book, Harry is still imprisoned allegedly for the rape and assault of Daphne Manners. The best section of this book was the interview he had with a policeman about what happened, why he was arrested, and Merrick’s part in the whole affair and his police misconduct. That is perhaps the most compelling part of the book, almost a deposition. The book mainly centers around Merrick, his attempts to relate to Sarah and Susan, two sisters who came to India from England, and the result when Merrick ends up going to the front in the army. WW II is still in progress. I felt as if we were in somewhat of a holding pattern through this book. I’m hoping the next one is better again. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16531473278767410773" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

